<h3>Publications and presentations on rhetorical figures</h3>

<p><a href="https://pdcnet.org/ajs/content/ajs_2019_0999_7_16_52">An Ontological Approach to Meaning Making through PATH and Gestalt Foregrounding in Climax</a>. With Lillian A Black (Senior author, formerly TW Black), Cliff O'Reilly, Yetian Wang, Paulo Pacheco, and Randy Allen Harris. 17 July 2019. <a href="https://www.pdcnet.org/collection-anonymous/browse?fp=ajs">The American Journal of Semiotics</a>. 

<p><a href="https://uwspace.uwaterloo.ca/handle/10012/14778">Collocation in Rhetorical Figures: A Case Study in Parison, Epanaphora and Homoioptoton</a> (<a href="http://github.com/ktu/figure-detection">Code</a>). 2019. UWSpace. Major research project, University of Waterloo. </p>

<p><a href="papers/rhetcan2019.pdf">Rhetorical figures as cognitive: A case study of Isocolon</a> (<a href="papers/rhetcan2019-slides.pdf">Slides</a>). The Canadian Society for the Study of Rhetoric. Vancouver, Canada. 4-6 June 19.</p> 

<p><a href="papers/rhetcan2019-gerberetal.pdf">A figure is a figure is a figure: Eight axioms toward a manifesto</a> (<a href="papers/rhetcan2019-gerberetal-slides.pdf">Slides</a>, <a href="papers/rhetcan2019-gerberetal-handout.pdf">handout</a>). With Kyle Gerber (Senior author), Danielle Bisnar-Griffin, and Randy Allen Harris. The Canadian Society for the Study of Rhetoric. Vancouver, Canada. 4-6 June 19.</p>
         
<p><a href="papers/ill12.pdf">Prosody as iconicity: isocolon's semantic and rhetorical homogeneity effects</a> (<a href="papers/ill12-slides.pdf">Slides</a>). Iconicity in Language and Literature. Lund, Sweden. 3-5 May 19.</p>

<p>A climactic ontology (<a href="papers/iacs2018-slides.pdf">Slides</a>). With Cliff O’Reilly (Senior author), Yetian Wang, Sarah Bott, Paulo Pacheco, TW Black, and Randy Allen Harris. International Association for Cognitive Semiotics. Toronto ON. 14 July 18.</p>

<p><a href="http://cmna.csc.liv.ac.uk/CMNA18/paper_01.pdf">Arguments in gradatio, incrementum and climax, a climax ontology.</a> With Cliff O’Reilly (Senior author), Yetian Wang, Katherine Tu, Sarah Bott, Paulo Pacheco, TW Black, and Randy Allen Harris. <a href="http://cmna.csc.liv.ac.uk/CMNA18/">CMNA XVIII - Computational Models of Natural Argument.</a> <a href="http://cmna.csc.liv.ac.uk/CMNA18/programme.html">Proceedings.</a> Liverpool, UK, 6 April 18. Presented by O’Reilly.</p>
